1 Theorecal preliminaries
In this course, were examining a proposed category, the complex predicate. Before we start looking
at the specics of this category, were going to consider some theorecal preliminaries about
categories in general. Pre-theorecally, there are two reasons why categories are useful.
(1) They capture one or more generalizaons that hold over a dataset
(2) They provide a springboard for advancing analysis of a dataset
There are two basic things that dene a category in classic terms.
(3) A set of criteria for determining whether a parcular token is a member of the category or
not
(4) One or more generalizaons, disnct from the membership criteria, that hold for all tokens
in the category, but which do not hold for any tokens outside the category
We dont want category membership to be random, with no membership criteria. Equally, if there
are membership criteria, then we dont want it to be the case that the membership criteria are the
only generalizaons that hold for the category. For example, if we propose a category of yellow balls,
we dont want it to be the case that the only generalizaons that hold of the category of yellow balls
are that its members are yellow and are balls. We want some other generalizaon, such as yellow
balls travel 1.5 mes faster than balls of any other colour.
As a minimum, we want at least two generalizaons to hold of all and only the members of a
category. One generalizaon acts as a membership criterion, and the other is a characterisc of the
category. While this is the ideal category, in fact many categories depart from this ideal as paerns in
datasets are very commonly not 100% vs 0%. Rather paerns might be 90% vs 10% and datasets are
analysed from quantave perspecves. The larger the membership, the harder it is to nd
generalizaons that apply to all of them. Under quantave approaches, there is oen a trade-o
between the extent of category membership and the number of generalizaons. As a constructed
example, we can consider two categories.
(5) Category A: Things whose vercal extension is greater than their horizontal extension
Category B: Things whose horizontal extension is greater than their vercal extension
Let us imagine that there are no generalizaons beyond the membership criteria that can be made
about these two categories. Given this, there is no evident benet to proposing Categories A and B.
Let us consider a slight variaon.
(6) Category A: Things whose vercal extension is not less than 10% greater than their
horizontal extension
Category B: Things whose horizontal extension is not less than 10% greater than their vercal
extension
Given this variaon, let us imagine then that there a signicant number of generalizaons, other
than membership criteria, can be made about each of Categories A and B. There is a signicant
2
benet to proposing Categories A and B, but it comes at the cost of excluding some data from either
of the categories.
Our aim today is to examine the proposed category of complex predicate from this
perspecve. There is a range of theorecal approaches to this concept and they dier as to
membership criteria, generalizaons that can be made, which data is excluded or included. Were
aiming to start on a cost/benet analysis. Well be looking at:
(7) Clarity of membership criteria
(8) Generalizaons that can be made
(9) Inclusion and exclusion of data
(10) Theorecal parsimony
Criteria (7) - (9) are reasonably self-evident, whereas criterion (10) is less self-evident. The basic point
of theorecal parsimony, commonly known as Occams Razor, is illustrated in (11) and (12).
(11) Dataset 1: Theorecal Analysis A with 15 principles
(12) Dataset 1: Theorecal Analysis B with 16 principles
On general grounds, Analysis A is preferred over Analysis B because it accounts for the same dataset
with a smaller number of principles. While this is an easy point to illustrate with constructed
examples, in pracce its oen very dicult to comparavely evaluate analyses against this criterion.
Analyses commonly dont cover exactly the same databases. In (11) and (12), Analysis A is more
parsimonious, but if we expanded the database, we might nd that Analysis A required 17 principles
to account for a larger database, whereas Analysis B could account for both the larger and the
smaller databases with 16 principles. Were not aiming to provide a detailed comparave evaluaon
of theories of complex predicaon against the criterion of parsimony. However, in our discussion, we
do note two long-established issues, set out in (13) and (14).
(13) morphemes
(14) Binary specicaon, + vs or + vs , as opposed to ternary specicaon, + vs vs
Many analyses make use of morphemes. The problem with morphemes is that it is oen unclear
what the falsicaon condions are for analyses involving morphemes. The issue with binary vs
ternary specicaon is that ternary specicaon increases the generave power of analyses, because
they oppose a negave specicaon to null specicaon. Determining the falsicaon condions for
analyses involving ternary specicaon is oen problemac.
2 Whats a predicate?
There are at least two principal uses of the term predicate in linguisc analysis. The use which is
probably most widely known is illustrated in (15).
(15) [The girl] + [saw the dog in the kennel]
Subject + Predicate
This is NOT the use of predicate that we are concerned with. Rather, we are concerned with the
philosophical denion of predicate, as set in Blackburn (2016).
3
A predicate expresses a condion that the enes referred to may sasfy, in which case the
resulng sentence will be true. For this reason a predicate may be thought of as a funcon
from things to sentences or even to truth-values.
Under this denion of the term predicate, the fundamental characterisc of the predicates is that
they license arguments and that simple clauses require a predicate to be interpretable. Consider
(15), The girl is the Subject, and not part of the Predicate. But in the philosophical logic approach,
both the girl and the dog are arguments of the predicate.
In terms of part-of-speech classes, verbs are the most prominent type of predicate. In (15),
the predicate is the verb see and its a simple predicate, which has two arguments. However,
predicates are not necessarily verbs, they can be other parts-of-speech such as adjecves and nouns.
(16) That woman is sick/a doctor.
In (16), the predicate is be sick or be a doctor and that woman is the argument.
Discussions of predicate and argument relaons commonly draw a disncon between
obligatory and oponal constuents, and this disncon is illustrated in (17).
(17) [The boy] saw [the bird] [from the car]
NP NP PP
In (17), the two NPs are obligatory, as they are required by the predicaonal verb see and they are
analysed as the obligatory arguments. Without them, the predicaon and the sentence would be
incomplete. By contrast, the PP is oponal and could be omied from the sentence without aecng
the grammacality of the sentence.
Blackburns philosophical denion discusses enes as arguments of predicates. However,
in many if not all languages, the arguments licensed by predicates are not limited to non-abstract
enes, as shown in (18) and (19).
(18) They said many words, not all of them truthful.
(19) She said I will go.
The predicate say licenses 2 arguments: an agent, and a theme. In (18), the theme is an enty, in
this case words. By contrast, in (19), the theme is not an enty. Rather, it is a proposion which
contains its own predicate go. The predicate say is a simple predicate and its not the only English
simple predicate which allows for an argument which contains its own predicate.
(20) I bet you $100 that they will go early.
The simple predicate bet in (20) licenses a proposional argument that they will go early. We will
call all arguments that contain their own predicates predicaonal arguments. They include
proposional arguments expressed by nite or non-nite clauses and arguments headed by
preposions, such as into the car in John persuaded Bill into the car.
So, it is the case that in English simple predicates can license predicaonal arguments as well
as enty arguments. In English, predicaonal arguments can appear in all argument posions,
including obligatory argument posions.
(21) [Drinking that last cup] lled the kid right up

In (21), the obligatory Subject posion is lled by a predicaonal argument. The situaon in
Australian languages is dierent. Across Australian languages, predicaonal arguments usually only
ll obligatory argument posions as Objects of locuonary verbs, and as Objects of predicates of
wanng and thinking (Hale 1976; Nordlinger 2006).
(22) japi-rni ka=rna=ngku kuyu ma-ninja-ku
ask-NPST PRES=1SGS=2SGO meat get-NML-PURP.COMP
I am asking you to get the meat. [Warlpiri Diconary]
From a cross-linguisc perspecve, enty arguments are prototypical whereas predicaonal
arguments are not. All languages permit nearly all argument posions to be mapped to enes. It is

the range of mappings found with predicaonal construcons varies greatly and for some languages,
such as Australian languages, there are very restricted mappings for predicaonal arguments.
3 Whats a complex predicate?
Having discussed simple predicates, we now turn to consider complex predicates. We begin by
illustrang English construcons that have been called complex predicates. One type of complex
predicate involves what have been called light verbs such as give, take, have in (23) - (25).
(23) Max walked. Max walked the dog.
(24) Max had a dog. Max took a dog. Max gave the kid a dog.
(25) Max had a walk. Max took a walk. Max gave the dog a walk.
In (23), we have a standard simple predicate walk with one argument and its causave counterpart
with two arguments. The sentences in (24) also involve simple predicates, have and take with two
arguments, and give with three arguments. The sentences in (25) have the same syntacc structure
as those in (24), but in terms of predicate-argument relaons The sentences in (25) involving have
and take have only one argument, Max, and the sentence involving give has only two arguments
Max and the dog.
This dierence in argument structure is described in terms of an opposion between light
and heavy or full verbs. In the sentences in (24), the verbs have, take, give appear as heavy verbs.
In the sentences in (25), they appear as light verbs. Light verbs are semancally bleached compared
with their heavy counterparts. As a heavy verb give involves transfer of something from one person
to another person. As a light verb, the recipient of give undergoes an acon performed by the
agent; the recipient doesn't receive anything.
One approach to addressing this heavy vs light disncon is to analyse the sentences in (25)
as involving complex predicates, as illustrated in (26) and (27).
(26) Simple predicates: walk (x), have (x, y), take (x, y), give (x, y, z)
(27) Complex predicates: have a walk (x), take a walk (x), give a walk (x, y)
This complex predicate analysis captures that fact that the combinaon of the light verb and a noun
phrase with a deverbal noun funcons in much the same way as the simple verb. This is a long-
standing claim in the literature, that the simple predicate construcons, and the complex predicate
construcons carry the same grammacal funcon acng as the predicate of a clause. Other
5
phrases in the clause are interpreted with respect to the predicate, whether as arguments expressed
by grammacal funcons such as subjects or objects or obliques, or as adjuncts modifying the
predicate or arguments of the predicate.
There are other construcons in English where predicate meanings appear to involve more
than one constuent. A very common construcon consists of a verb and an intransive preposion,
as illustrated in (28) and (29).
(28) (a) Max ate up his dinner. (b) Max ate his dinner up. (c) Max ate his dinner.
(29) (a) Max ran up a bill. (b) Max ran a bill up. (c) Max ran the event.
This construcon has been called a phrasal verb or a verb parcle construcon. Examples (28) and
(29) each consist of single clauses (monoclausal). In these clauses ate, run and up are
independent words, as shown by the alternaon in posion of up between the (a) and (b)
sentences. In (28) and (29) Max is the subject, his dinner is the object in (28), and a bill or the
event are the objects in (29). The forms, ate and up, together describe what Max does to the
dinner, while ran and up together describe what Max does to the bill. The (c) sentences show
single clauses with single verbs whose funcon parallels that of ate up and ran up in the (a) and (b)
sentences.
A dierence between eat up and run up is that run up seems to be an idiomac phrase.
??Max ran a bill is hard to assign a meaning to, while Max ate his dinner is a normal sentence. Eat
up parallels nish up, e up, break up, cut up, where up conveys a vague meaning of
compleon. That is, the meaning of some phrasal verbs is non-composional (highly lexicalised),
while the meaning of other phrasal verbs is more composional.
We may note that there is a signicant dierence between the phrasal verb and the light
verb construcons in English. There is a dierence in argument structure between the light and
heavy verb construcons. With phrasal verbs, there is no dierence in argument structure between
the simple and the complex construcons, when relaons between the simple and complex
construcons are non-idiomac, as in (28).
(30) eat (x,y), eat up (x, y)
Given that the complex construcon does not appear to aect argument structure, this raises a
queson as to whether phrasal verbs should be analysed as complex predicates. Phrasal verbs are
undoubtedly syntaccally complex, but there is a queson as to whether this syntacc complexity
should necessarily be mapped to an analysis of predicaonal complexity.
When we extend our search beyond English, we nd that the label complex predicate has
been applied to a very large range of syntacc structures, catalogued in (31) (Anderson 2011;
Bowern 2008: 162165; Osgarby & Bowern 2023).
(31) Abstract nal and biparte verb stems, Associated path construcons, Auxiliary
construcons, Light verb construcons, Noun incorporaon construcons, Phrasal verbs,
Preposion incorporaon construcons, Raising verbs, Restructuring predicates, Serial verb
construcons, Verbal classier construcons
We are looking at some of these construcons and considering whether the label complex predicate
is equally applicable to them all, and whether it is a useful category which allows us to make
generalisaons about linguisc phenomena.

4 Creang a database of complex predicates
When creang a database, the rst queson to be addressed is the nature of the category under
invesgaon. If youre interested in invesgang the opposion between yellow balls and balls of
other colours, then collecng informaon on trees is not going to advance your invesgaon. For the
category of complex predicate, the major opons as to what kind of a category it might be are set
out in (32) - (34).
(32) The category of complex predicate is delimited by semanc criteria. This semanc category
may be mapped to a variety of syntacc construcons.
(33) The category of complex predicate is delimited by morphosyntacc criteria. This
morphosyntacc construcon may be mapped to a variety of semanc categories.
(34) The category of complex predicate is delimited by both semanc and morphosyntacc
criteria. There may be mulple mappings between semancs and morphosyntax.
A fourth possibility is that the label complex predicate doesnt actually label a category at all,
whether syntacc or semanc. It labels construcons which resemble each other, but which dont t
the denion of category given earlier; i.e. there are not enough properes shared by putave
members, and not enough generalisaons over the members.
We do not aim to provide a comprehensive evaluaon of the three opons in (32) - (34)
which do dene a category. We will be examining the category of complex predicate from both
semanc and syntacc perspecves without assigning a priority to either. For most Australian
languages, there are comparavely limited descripve materials. There is usually more extensive
informaon on construcon types than on semanc categories relang to predicaon. Consequently,
our database focuses on construcon types.
There are two components to this database. The rst component is an inventory of
construcon types. The second component is the set of tokens assignable to each construcon type.
Well be looking at both aspects, the inventory of construcon types and the token sets that go with
each construcon type. Consideraons of producvity and systemacity are central to determining
what data gets included in our database for the category complex predicate. If run up in (29) was
the only example of a phrasal verb in English, then we wouldnt be spending me analysing it.
However, there is a comparable construcon with exactly the same intransive preposion up
which seems to be more producve in that it appears with dierent verbs. Moreover, other
intransive preposions can appear in similar construcons: break o a branch, cut out a piece,
think something through.
Finding objecve bases for determining whether a parcular construcon is systemac
and/or producve is a complex issue and not something that we are examining here. Its quite
possible for a construcon to be quantavely predominant but unproducve. Equally, its possible
for construcons to be quantavely uncommon but producve. These two possibilies can be
illustrated with Murrinhpatha complex verbal construcons (Manseld 2019: 194195).

We begin by considering delimitaons proposed in the current literature. Denions of
complex predicates focus on three criteria: (i) being mul-morphemic; (ii) monoclausality; (iii) match
to equivalent simple predicate structures.
(37) Mul-morphemic
Complex predicates can be dened as predicates which are mul-headed; they are
composed of more than one grammacal element (either morphemes or words), each of
which contributes part of the informaon ordinarily associated with a head. (Alsina, Bresnan
& Sells 1997: 1)
(38) Monoclausality
the term complex predicate is used to designate a construcon that involves two or more
predicaonal elements (such as nouns, verbs, and adjecves) which predicate as a single
unit, i.e. their arguments map onto a monoclausal syntacc structure.(Bu 2010: 49)
(39) Match to equivalent simple predicate structures
We propose that merger construcons class fundamentally with monomorphemic
predicates. (Baker & Harvey 2010: 19)
1
a complex verbal predicate is a mulword head if it exhibits the same syntacc behavior (and
marks the same categories) as a simple verb. (Bowern 2010: 46)
We rst consider the mul-morphemic criterion. We then consider the monoclausality and match to
simple predicate structures criteria together as there is signicant overlap between the two.
4.1 Mul-morphemic
Complex predicates can consist of independent words such as run and up, or even phrases such as
a look in have a look. The requirement seems to be for disnguishable phonological expression of
at least two parts of the complex predicate. The interpretaon of the requirement for disnguishable
phonological expression is itself subject to disnct interpretaons. Does the requirement for disnct
expression operate at the level of the morpheme or that of the word? This is what previous
researchers have said.

The dierence between the two criteria can be illustrated with denominal inchoaves and

(42) kimuk-me kimuk-wo
big-INCH big-CAUS

The inchoave and causave meanings illustrated in (42) are prototypical examples of predicate
meanings. However, both -me Inchoave nor -wo Causave are standardly analysed as suxes and
not as words. They cannot occur independently, they do not constute independent prosodic words,
and they have a xed posion immediately following a nominal root. As suxes, they are producve
and the meanings of forms involving these suxes is composional. Under Bowerns criterion, the
forms in (42) are not complex predicates because they do not consist of two words. Under the Alsina
et al criterion, the forms in (42) are complex predicates because they consist of two disnct
morphemes.
In this case, the queson is whether there is a well-movated basis for including word-hood
as a criterion. Morpho-syntaccians dier as to the status of words. Those who argue that there is a
major dierence between words and phrases in terms of composionality and visibility to syntacc
operaons will not treat morphologically constructed causaves and inchoaves as complex
predicates. Those who take the division between words and phrases as arbitrary can then treat as
complex predicates examples such as the causaves and inchoaves in Bininj Gunwok and many
Australian languages., and these meanings are expressed by suxes and not by words. As the nature
of databases is central to our invesgaon and our invesgaon is an inial invesgaon, we take a
wider scope and follow Alsina et al and analyse the forms in (42) as complex predicates. However, we
recognise that fuller invesgaon may provide well movated reasons for taking a narrower scope
with word-hood as a criterion.

4.1.1 What we exclude single words
The key point of the mul-morpheme criterion is that there must be more than one word or
morpheme. However, some syntacc theories allow zero morphemes. In this secon we describe
construcons that have been analysed as containing zero morphemes. We exclude them from
'complex predicates' on the basis of absence of phonological expression. English has construcons
relang intransive verbs to transive verbs. Some stand in the inchoave/causave relaon (crack,
break): others in an acon/derived acon relaon (gallop the horse, walk the dog). There is no overt
morpheme marking this relaon. Consider the two sentences in (43) and (44).
9
(43) I was standing near to the edge of the cli and the rock just cracked, nothing, no obvious
reason.
(44) I got a hammer and cracked the rock.
The two uses of crack in (43) and (44) evidently have dierent argument structures. The crack in
(43) is a change-of-state inchoave. The crack in (44) is a change-of-state causave. In English,
crack is there is no overt morphological realizaon of the fact that inchoave crack is a predicate
with 1 argument and causave crack is a predicate with 2 arguments. This marked relaonship is
at least semiproducve.
(45) I was sing at the computer and the data just corrupted in front of my eyes, nothing, no
obvious reason.
(46) I put a virus into the soware and corrupted the data.
All semanc analyses have to recognise the disncon between the inchoave and causave
interpretaons and more importantly the systemac and producve relaonship between the two.
Theres a wide range in proposals as to how this semanc disncon maps to syntacc structure, but
many hypotheses posit that the inchoave and the causave have disnct syntacc structures, at
some or all levels of syntacc structure.
One common analysis would be that the crack causave meaning involves two predicates, a
predicate with the meaning crack having substanve phonological expression and a causave
predicate which is a morpheme. Under this line of analysis, the crack causave meaning could be
classied as a complex predicate because it involves two predicates. This line of analysis goes back
originally to work in generave semancs, and there are many versions of this approach, see Denniss
(2023) for a summary.
However, a fundamental issue for this line of analysis is that it relies on zero morphemes.
There is extensive debate over zero morphemes, whether zero morphemes should form part of
analysis at all, and if they do, the nature of constraints on the posing of zero morphemes (Dahl &
Fbregas 2018). Consequently, allowing zero morphemes in the database for complex predicates
necessarily raises serious problems for delimitaon. Therefore, we follow many theories of complex
predicaon in requiring that all structural elements must have disnguishable non-zero phonological
realizaons. As such, under our approach, crack in (44) is not a complex predicate, even though
semancally it consists of a state which can be entered (inchoave) or caused (causave).
By contrast with English, in many Australian languages, inchoave/causave pairs are
realized with two phonologically disnct constuents.

4.2 Monoclausality and match to simple predicate structures
The monoclausality criterion is repeated here for convenience.
the term complex predicate is used to designate a construcon that involves two or more
predicaonal elements (such as nouns, verbs, and adjecves) which predicate as a single
unit, i.e. their arguments map onto a monoclausal syntacc structure.(Bu 2010: 49)
While this criterion is intuively appealing, it raises a queson.
(49) What are the independent criteria for determining that a syntacc structure is monoclausal?
Its surprisingly dicult to nd independent criteria for monoclausality. One candidate appears to be
negaon.
We rely on the criterion of lack of independent negaon as a crosslinguiscally applicable
test for clausehood. (Bohnemeyer et al. 2007: 501)
However, in pracce, independent negaon is a problemac criterion. English is a good example of
why its problemac. The English negator not negates at all syntacc levels from the word upwards.
(50) Well extend the discount to the not really juniors/really not juniors.
As such, the lack of independent negaon as a criterion has a very limited scope in English. This is
also the case in other languages.
Analysis of the constraints on argument mapping appears to oer more widely applicable
criteria for monoclausality. As we will see, there are signicant constraints on argument mapping in
syntacc construcons involving only a single simple predicate. Construcons involving only a single
simple predicate are uncontroversially monoclausal. We posit that mapping constraints are invariant
in monoclausal structures, regardless of whether the predicate is simple or complex. Consequently, if
a construcon involving more than one predicaonal constuent is subject to the same constraints
as construcons with simple predicates, then the complex construcon is monoclausal and involves a
complex predicate.
To illustrate the constraints that hold on monoclausal construcons with simple predicates, it
is helpful to begin by considering some argument mapping paerns that are possible in some types
of complex verbal construcons, but which are not possible in monoclausal construcons. We may
consider the Chinese serial verb construcon in (51).
(51) w qi t dibio w
1SG beg 3SG represent 1SG
I begged her/him to represent me. Mandarin Chinese (Li & Thompson 1981: 607)
In (51), there are two verb predicates, qi and dibio, They act independently. The same enty I,
me maps to two disnct arguments, the agent argument of beg and the paent argument of
represent. Conversely t acts as the paent of 'beg' and the agent of 'represent'. It might be argued
that qi and dibio form a complex predicate. But there are two pieces of evidence against this. If
(51) were monoclausal, then the paent of dibiao should be reexive, as it is co-referenal with the
11
subject w, but it is not. The second piece of evidence has to do with the arguments and their
mapping to grammacal funcons. In (51) there are two disnct agents and two disnct themes. A
monoclausal structure with a simple predicate can only have one instance of each argument relaon.
A number of analyses oer formal versions of these two constraints, e.g. Baker & Harvey (2010),
Brjars (2020: 161) for LFG and the Funcon-Argument Bi-uniqueness constraint.
These constraints have signicant potenal when we consider complex verbal construcons.
We can consider the English sentence in (52).
(52) Seeing the beauful city thrilled the traveller.
The queson is whether we should analyse this complex construcon as involving a complex
predicate see + thrill. In (52), there are two dierent sources of experience - the city for see, seeing
the city for thrill - and simple predicates allow only one source of experience. Consequently, (52) is
not an example of a monoclausal structure and not an example of a complex predicate. The
constraint against mulple instances of either the same semanc relaon or mulple instances of
the same grammacal relaon excludes many construcons involving predicaonal arguments, such
as (53).
(53) The dog barking noisily had seen me.
On inial inspecon, one potenal analysis appears to be the complex predicate analysis in (54)
(54) bark-see (the dog, me)
However, bark and see do not have the same Subject. The Subject of bark is the dog and that of
see is the dog barking noisily. A complex predicate analysis would necessitate two disnct Subjects.
4.3 Summary
Under our analysis, the database for the analysis of the category complex predicate includes tokens
with the following characteriscs.
(55) Informaon on predicaon comes from two or more phonologically disnct sources
(56) The mapping between arguments and constuents is subject to the same constraints as
those which operate with simple predicates.
In combinaon, these two criteria exclude a signicant number of complex verbal construcons from
the category of complex predicate. We are now going to examine three complex verbal
construcons which are widespread in Australia and consider their relaonship to the category of
complex predicate.
(57) Associated path construcons, Coverb/preverb + verb construcons, Light verb construcons
However, before looking at these construcons, we will rst examine the problemac category of
Auxiliary, as this category plays a signicant role in analyses of the category of complex predicate.

5 Auxiliary construcons
It is generally agreed that the label Auxiliary is applied to a diverse range of morphemes, including, in
Australian languages, pronominal clic complexes. However, the prototypical examples of auxiliaries
are auxiliary verbs, and it is potenal auxiliary verbs that we are concerned with here. From our
perspecve, the queson is whether something described as an Auxiliary is predicaonal or not. Falk
(2008: 861) presents the choice between the two analyses for English. Working with the example in
(58), there are two potenal analyses, either the auxiliary verb will is the head of the sentence (59),
or the lexical verb take is the head of the sentence (60).
(58) The children will take syntax.
(59) Predicaonal analysis: will is the head of the sentence, and [take syntax] is a complement of
will
(60) Non-predicaonal analysis: take is the head of the sentence, and will is a modier or
morphological marker expressing/realizing future tense.
Falk proposes that English auxiliaries vary with some being predicaonal, such as the progressive be
auxiliary and others being non-predicaonal such as the perfect have auxiliary. Falk dierenates the
two on the basis of paradigmac opposions with other verbs. As illustrated in (61), the progressive
be is in an apparent paradigm with other clearly predicaonal verbs.
(61) a. The children were taking syntax.
b. The children started taking syntax.
c. The children kept taking syntax.
d. The children stopped taking syntax.
By contrast, the perfect have does not have clearly predicaonal counterparts, since the perfect
parciple cannot follow other verb as in (62).
(62) The children have/*nish/*complete taken syntax.
However, the paradigms in (61) are not the only paradigmac paerns to be considered in relaon to
the English progressive be.
(63) The children were/sat/stood/lay eang bread.
The verb be is an intransive stave verb. The verbs sit i. stand, lie are intransive and usually stave.
Sit can funcon as an inchoave, though inchoave meanings are more usually realized by the
phrasal verb sit down. In (63), the sit verb is stave. Though both be and the stance verbs funcon as
intransive staves, their paradigmac potenals are not the same.
(64) The children sat, Alice eang bread, Jane eang cheese, Max eang apples.
(65) *The children were, Alice eang bread, Jane eang cheese, Max eang apples.
With the evidently predicaonal verb sit, the following parciple has an open Subject argument
posion, lled by Alice, Jane, Max etc. By contrast, with the auxiliary be, the following parciple lacks
an open argument posion. Given this, we suggest that the tradional analysis of both progressive
be and perfect have as non-predicaonal is beer supported. However, we agree with Falks general
13
point, that while the default assumpon may be that any verb labelled as an auxiliary is non-
predicaonal, the specic paerning of each individual auxiliary must be examined.

In all three languages, Associated Path construcons have the same morphosyntacc structure. They
consist of a lexical verb in a non-nite form and path verb in a nite form. There is debate about
whether the non-nite lexical verb and the nite verb are independent words, or whether they are
morphologically bound. The conjugaonal paradigm of the path verb may or may not be idencal to
the paradigm of an independent lexical verb. Thus, in Anmatyerr the root ape can appear either as a
path verb or as a main verb with the meaning go, and the same is true of ya in Warlpiri. Historically,
it would appear that all path verbs derive from main verbs. However, synchronically, in some
languages path verbs do not necessarily have main verb counterparts: e.g. Kaytetye (Panther &
Harvey 2020: 83), and in Warumungu the associated path forms comprise portmanteau inecons
with tense and aspect (Simpson 2002).
In structural terms, the Associated Path construcon has signicant parallels with light verb
construcons in the Australian languages we have examined so far. Both consist of an inial non-
nite constuent and a following nite verbal constuent (or verbal inecon). The two
construcons generally dier in the internal morphosyntax of the non-nite constuent. In the
Associated Path construcon, the non-nite constuent is always either a derived form of the verb,
or is the base for an Associated Path inecon. In light verb construcons, the non-nite constuent
(e.g. a coverb) is usually underived. However, there are some light verb construcons which involve
derived non-nite constuents. The dierence in the status of the non-nite constuent is not the
most important dierence between Associated Path construcons and light verb construcons. The
most important dierence lies in argument structure and case assignment, as shown in (80) - (83).
(80) ane-ye alpe-yayne aynanthe

In Associated Path construcons, it is the lexical, non-nite constuent which determines the
argument structure and case-marking of the overall construcon In (80) and (82)the sit verb is
intransive and the subject has the unmarked case (Nominave in Kaytetye, and Absoluve in

the case frame of see, and not by the case frame of intransive RETURN. Similarly in (83), the subject
(agent of throw, and actor of MOVE.FAST) is Ergave, determined by the case frame of throw. This
is the opposite of the situaon with the construcons in Secon 6 where the nite constuent
determines the valency of the overall construcon, whether it is a light verb or a full lexical verb.
This raises a fundamental queson about whether to include Associated Path construcons
in the category of complex predicates. The cost of including Associated Path construcons in the
category of complex predicates is the loss of generalisaon about argument structure in complex
predicate construcons. This, in turn, necessarily raises the queson of how Associated Path
construcons fare against the criteria we have proposed for complex predicates, which are repeated
here as (84) and (85) for convenience.
(84) Informaon on predicaon comes from two or more phonologically disnct sources
(85) The mapping between arguments and constuents is subject to the same constraints as
those which operate with simple predicates.
If Associated Path construcons are complex predicates, then they evidently sasfy phonological
criterion in (84). Evaluaon against argument criterion in (85)is not equivalently straighorward.
There are two principal hypotheses, as set out in (86) and (87).
(86) Hypothesis 1: The lexical verb licenses one or more enty arguments. The Path verb licenses
an enty argument. There is a procedure for reconciling the argument(s) of the Path verb
with argument(s) of the lexical verb at the construcon level. LexV(a, b) + Path V(c) and (a)
merges with (c)
(87) Hypothesis 2: The lexical verb licenses one or more enty arguments. The Path verb licenses
a predicaonal phrasal argument, which is lled by the lexical verb and its argument
structure. The enty arguments of the overall construcon are inherited from the lexical
verb Path V (LexV(a, b))
The crical data for the comparave evaluaon of these two hypotheses is the fact that Path verbs
appear with both acve and stave lexical verbs. When the lexical verb is an intransive stave verb,
the argument of the lexical verb is a theme. To sasfy the argument mapping condion, if the Path
17
verb has an argument, then that argument would also have to be a theme. Path verbs may also
appear when the lexical verb is a transive acve verb with agent and theme arguments. However, in
this case, the argument of the Path verb is co-referenal with the agent. Consequently, the argument
of the Path verb would necessarily be an agent.
Overall, therefore, Hypothesis 1 is not supported. By contrast, Hypothesis 2 is able to
accommodate this data. Therefore, we do not analyse Associated Path construcons as complex
predicates. Rather, the Path verb is an auxiliary verb which takes a predicaonal phrasal argument.
Two detailed analyses of the syntax of Associated Path construcons in detail also propose an
auxiliary analysis.: Panther and Harvey (2020) for Kaytetye, and Laughren (2010: 174182), while
Simpson (2001) proposes a merger of argument structure in Warlpiri Associated Path construcons
that dierenates them from the clear auxiliary verb construcons of Diyari and other Karnic
languages.
It should be noted that this evaluaon is dependent on the Path verb appearing with both
stave and acve lexical verbs. There are languages with a number of Path construcons, and the
semancs and syntax of these Path construcons requires further research: e.g. Kaytetye (Panther &
Harvey 2020). It is possible that some Path construcons may be limited to acve lexical verbs and if
so, this would require re-evaluaon of Hypotheses 1 and 2.

8 An alternave analysis of light verb construcons
Denniss (2023) presents a very interesng alternave to the analyses of light verb construcons that
weve presented. Her research focuses on Ngarinyman from the Victoria River district. Verbal
structures in Ngarinyman are essenally the same as those found in Wagiman and Warlpiri. There is
a closed inventory of nite verbs and a large open class of coverbs. The size of the closed class varies.
Ngarinyman has 19 verbs, Wagiman has 43 verbs, and Warlpiri has 130 verbs (Denniss 2023: 44;
Kraue & Harvey 2021: 106; Nash 2008). Denniss proposes the following axioms for her analysis.
(88) Verbs are always light, even if they are the sole predicate in a clause
(89) Coverbs are acategorial roots which do not have a predicaonal structure
In other words, there are no complex predicates. Only verbs supply predicate structure. In terms of
semancs, verbs supply generic informaon whereas coverbs supply encyclopedic informaon. The
meaning of verbs as main verbs is determined by a non-linguisc system of meaning.
[Verbs] acquire a cognive default interpretaon as a verb of physical moon in space. If this
is the case, then any apparent meaning dierences between light and heavy verbs are not
due to lexical or syntacc properes, but instead due to a whole other dimension of
meaning outside the narrow linguisc system that consistently unies with syn-sem
structure (Ramchand 2014: 240)
We can note here that its central to this line of analysis that meaning can be paroned into various
categories. The opposion between generic and encyclopedic knowledge appears to be very similar
to the long-standing grammacal (generic) vs lexical (encyclopedic) opposion. However, all of these
18
proposals for paroning meaning into categories face the same problem, which is the absence of
objecve criteria for assigning meanings to categories.
Another construct which is central to this line of analysis is the zero morpheme. We have
already discussed the issues with zero morphemes. Under this line of analysis, the English transive
crack consists of an acategorial root crack and a causave morpheme. The merger of these two
morphemes is a post-syntacc operaon (Denniss 2023: 7). This disncon between syntacc and
post-syntacc faces the same problem as that facing the paroning of meaning. There do not
appear to be objecve criteria for determining whether a parcular grammacal component is
syntacc or post-syntacc.
These problems about paroning meaning and disnguishing syntacc vs post-syntacc are
issues that face many theories. Now, were going to consider the advantages of adopng this
approach, despite the fact that there are some fundamental unresolved issues. The rst predicon is
that if coverbs are roots and all roots are acategorial, then coverbs should be able to appear with a
range of syntacc funcons, and this is in fact the case.
(90) wawirri pan-karla pa-npa kurlarda-rlu rdilyki-ngki

You can't spear a kangaroo with a broken spear. [Warlpiri] (Hale eldnotes)
Thus in (90), the coverb rdilyki appears in a nominal syntacc posion and takes nominal case
marking. Approximately 20% of Warlpiri coverbs are aested in nominal syntacc posions. Its in
fact the case that in most languages with coverbs that some forms can appear as both nominals and
coverbs. However, in the languages which we are familiar with, appearance in both coverb and

as to why alternaon between coverb and nominal syntacc posions is not more widely aested.
Under a complex predicate analysis, one approach would be to analyse rdilyki as a
straighorward nominal. Nominals are oponally predicaonal and when appearing with light verbs
in Warlpiri, it is the predicaonal version which appears. Under this approach, nominal + light verb

The advantages of the Denniss approach are summarized in (96) and the disadvantages in

As discussed, the disadvantages are generic and not limited to this parcular theorecal approach

9 Summary
In scienc terms, the purpose of establishing a category is to draw some generalizaons over the
category. There is no scienc value in establishing a category for which there are no generalizaons.
Establishing a category requires that there be independent criteria for deliming the category, for
determining which tokens are to be excluded from the database. Having established a category, the
requirement is then that there are generalizaons, independent of the denional criteria, which
hold across the category. There is no consensus in the exisng literature on either denional criteria
or generalizaons for the proposed category of complex predicate. As noted in the introducon,
there is usually a trade-o between the number of denional criteria, the size of the category, and
the potenal for generalizaons. The greater the number of denional criteria, the smaller the size
of the category, and the easy it is to draw generalizaons. We consider these trade-os in this
secon.
As discussed in the introducon, analyses of the category complex predicate have proposed
three delimitaon principles:
(98) Mul-morphemic or mul-word
(99) Monoclausality
(100) Match to equivalent simple predicate structures
The choice between mul-morphemic or mul-word has signicant implicaons for the category, as
mul-word is a more restricve criterion than mul-morphemic. If the criterion is mul-morphemic,
then there is a major issue with this criterion as to whether zero morphemes are included or not. If
zero morphemes are included, then in praccal terms, this condion eecvely isnt a criterion
because only a miniscule number of tokens are excluded. If zero morphemes are excluded, then the
criterion does have signicant exclusionary capacity.
Similarly, being monoclausal is a necessary condion for a condion to be classied as a
complex predicate. However, in pracce, there dont appear to be a lot of independent criteria for
determining whether a construcon is monoclausal or not. In individual languages, evidence from
independent negaon and from reexivisaon (domain of anaphor binding) may be relevant and
worth taking into consideraon. From a general, cross-linguisc perspecve, we have suggested that
monoclausality and match to simple predicate structures be combined into a single condion
requiring that argument mapping relaons in complex predicates are subject to the same constraints
as found with simple predicates. This criterion has signicant exclusionary capacity.
There is a further criterion which is implicit in the term complex predicate, but which we
have not thus far explicitly considered. This criterion is that in any construcon classed as a complex
predicate all constuents of the complex predicate must have the capacity to contribute to the
determinaon of argument structure. In light verb construcons, the constuents do have the
capacity to contribute to the determinaon of argument structure. Consequently, light verb
construcons may be classied as complex predicates. As a contrast we may consider the producve
English phrasal verb construcon, as exemplied by eat vs eat up. In the phrasal verb construcon,
the preposion does not contribute to the determinaon of argument structure. Consequently, while
the producve English phrasal verb construcon is a complex verbal construcon, it is not necessarily
a complex predicate, if the requirement for contribuon to determinaon of argument structure is
included as a denional criterion for the category of complex predicate
If these three denional criteria are adopted, then the category of complex predicate has a
fairly narrow membership: construcons involving more than one substanve morpheme where
both morphemes contribute to the determinaon of argument structure and the resulng argument
21
structure conforms to the limitaons on simple predicate argument structures. Given this
comparavely narrow category, it is possible to draw an independent generalizaon. If one of the
constuents is clearly verbal and the other is not, then the verbal constuent determines overall
argument structure.
However, its an open queson whether deliming the complex predicate category this
narrowly is the most protable approach. For example, if the third criterion of contribuon to
argument structure was not denional, then there would be a larger category. This larger category
would, for example, include producve English preposional verbs. The quesons to be examined
are what other construcons would be included and what generalizaons could be drawn across the
larger category.
10 Further research
One important queson is how the capacity to determine argument structure is best modelled. In
many ways, the simplest model is for this capacity to be listed in the lexicon. All models agree that
the lexical entries for verbs in Australian languages have specicaons for argument structure. It
follows from this specicaon that verbs in Australian languages cannot appear in non-predicaonal
posions and this is the case.
The situaon with coverbs and nominals is problemac. If the lexical entries for coverbs and
nominals involve specicaon for argument structure, then the predicon is nominals and coverbs
should be able to head predicaonal arguments. However, in most Australian languages, this does
not appear to be case, as in the constructed Wagiman example in (101).
(101) *jamh-ma lamang gunubuya liwa
eat-NPV meat snking bad
Eang snking meat is bad.
On the other hand, if there is no informaon about argument structure in their lexical entries, then
their appearance should be unrestricted and this also is not the case.
(102) *nyenh-yi ng-a-n-bu-ng
be.quiet-erg PST-1SG-3AGT-hit-PP
The quiet one hit me.
Coverbs cannot take core case marking in most languages with coverbs. Both coverbs and nominals
can appear in predicaonal posions without any other substanve material. If the predicaonal
structure is not in the lexicon, then the most obvious place where it could be is in syntacc structure.
However, the only way that this can be made to work is with the use of zero morphemes and there
dont appear to be any substanve constraints on the use of zero morphemes.
What were looking for is a principled analysis which accounts for two paerns. The rst
paern is the appearance of coverbs and nominals in posions which license arguments. The second
paern is the restricted occurrence of coverbs in posions which dont license arguments, preferably
without resort to zero morphemes.
